Shhh‚Ä¶ do you hear that? It‚Äôs the sound of World Listening Day approaching on July 18. World Listening Day was established in 2010, and each year the holiday has a specific theme tied to it. Past themes include ‚ÄúH20,‚Äù ‚ÄúSounds Lost & Found,‚Äù and ‚ÄúListen to You!‚Äù This year‚Äôs theme is ‚ÄúListening to the Ground,‚Äù which asks us to consider the sounds of the literal ground in all its surfaces, from soil to asphalt, whether we‚Äôre losing metaphorical ground, and whether we can find new ground by listening for it. So quiet down, open up your ears, and get ready to study soundscapes on World Listening Day.
https://nationaltoday.com/world-listening-day/
https://www.worldlisteningproject.org/

The County of Santa Clara is making it even simpler for people to schedule COVID-19 testing appointments online. Choose from a list of all available drive thru testing sites and appointment times throughout Santa Clara County. Anyone can be tested and there are no requirements for testing criteria, insurance, or immigration status.
To schedule a free test, go to www.scvmc.org/covid19testing or visit www.sccfreetest.org
You can also call 1-888-334-1000 to make an appointment in English, Spanish, Vietnamese or Chinese. Schedule your free test today!

post_text:
Help keep our kids and community safe this Fourth of July.
All types of fireworks, even those labeled 'safe and sane' are illegal in San Jos√© and most of Santa Clara County.
In 2017, the National Fire Protection Association reported U.S. hospital emergency rooms treated an estimated 12,900 people for fireworks-related injuries. Children younger than 15 years of age accounted for more than one-third (36%) of those injuries. Fireworks also start an average of 18,500 fires per year, including 1,300 structure fires, 300 vehicle fires, and 16,900 outside and other fires.

post_text: ‚ÄúJuneteenth,‚Äù celebrated each June 19th, is the oldest nationally celebrated commemoration of the ending of slavery in the United States. It was on this day in 1865, more than two years after the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1, 1863, that Union soldiers arrived in Galveston, Texas to announce the Civil War had ended and the enslaved were now free. This day also provides us an opportunity to reflect and honor its significance.
shared_text:
Santa Clara County Office of Education
June 19 at 1:30 PM ¬∑

SCCOE honors this day of resilience in the face of injustice and inhumanity for now and future generations. We simultaneously acknowledge the historical relevance of this significant event and the generational trauma that accompanies being subject to racism, discrimination and prejudice as a barrier to positive mental and physical health and well-being, economic opportunity, and academic achievement. We invite you to join with us today, and every day, to celebrate the strength and resilience of the African American community.

Due to everyone‚Äôs collective efforts to shelter in place, recent updates to the Shelter-in-Place Order expands more allowable businesses and activities effective June 5. Please remember this does not mean the pandemic is over. It means that we have successfully slowed the spread of the virus to allow certain workforce sectors to reopen with Social Distancing Protocols to keep themselves and the community safe. The Shelter In Place Order is still in effect, has no expiration date and is to be carried out until further notice. This is an evolving situation and the County is constantly assessing the various factors and strategies needed to ease restrictions in the safest manner possible.
For an overview of changes that came into effect June 5, read the executive summary: https://direc.to/egNi

‚ÄúIt is the supreme art of the teacher to awaken joy in creative expression and knowledge.‚Äù ‚Äì Albert Einstein

Hey KIND humans! Happy Teacher Appreciation Week! What a perfect time to post this video of one amazing, dynamic human who impacts children's lives everyday. This interview was a tearjerker. Laurie has been an art teacher for almost 30 years! Her dedication and unwavering passion brought us to tears. Happy tears, of course! There is no question she is deeply committed to her students and her job. Can we all have teachers like Laurie?! San Jose is a mixing pot of cultures and demographics, how does a teacher not only teach, but also connect with each and every one of her students? Take a listen‚Ä¶

post_text: Join us tomorrow as we celebrate Dolores Huerta Day. An American labor leader and civil rights activist, Dolores Clara Fern√°ndez Huerta (born April 10, 1930) joined Cesar Chavez as co-founder of the National Farmworkers Association (later known as the United Farm Workers (UFW). Helping organize California's 1965 Delano grape strike, Huerta was the lead negotiator in the workers' contract created after the strike. To learn more about this incredible woman, please visit: https://doloreshuerta.org/dolores-huerta-day-curriculum/

post_text: New update from County of Santa Clara Public Health. If you need to leave your house for essential activities, it is recommended you wear a medical cloth face mask to help stop the spread of the virus.
shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
April 2 at 8:41 PM ¬∑

When going out for essential activities, we recommend that members of the public should wear reusable, non-medical cloth face coverings. This will prevent you from unintentionally spreading the virus even if you have no or very few symptoms. Medical masks (N-95s and surgical masks) are in short supply and should be used by healthcare professionals who need them in order to continually provide care for our community.

Wearing a face covering is not a substitute for sheltering in place, physical distancing of 6-feet, or frequent hand washing. When everyone wears a face covering, it signals that we are all protecting each other and reinforces physical distancing of 6-feet. Wearing a face covering may reduce exposure to droplets if someone near you is infected and coughs or sneezes.

Always wash your hands, or use a hand sanitizer, before and after touching your face or face covering. Why? If you are infected, you do not want to contaminate your hands. If you are not infected, you do not want to inoculate yourself with contaminated hands.

shared_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
March 15 at 8:00 AM ¬∑

What is Social Distancing? Social distancing means to avoid congregate settings, mass gatherings, and maintaining distance (approximately 6 feet or 2 meters) from others whenever possible. The goals for using mitigation strategies in communities with local COVID-19 transmission are to slow the transmission of disease and to protect. #coronavirus

The County Public Health Department issued mandatory order prohibiting public or private gatherings of more than 100 people taking effect at 12:00 a.m. on March 14, 2020 (for at least three weeks). Public Health is also banning gatherings of 35 to 100 people unless certain conditions are met to reduce the likelihood of transmission at those events. Read the new County guidance from March 13, 2020 at https://www.sccgov.org/sites/phd/DiseaseInformation/novel-coronavirus/Pages/COVID-19-Guidance-031320.aspx

post_text: San Jos√© Unified Families - did you know your student has access to a variety of wonderful (and free) online resources through the school district?
